                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d460">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4386: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Harbin</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hanson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Harbin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-05-26T15:00:00+08:26">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 26, 1922—3 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received May 27—8:58 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Chinese Eastern Railway station agent at Suifenho telegraphs that mutiny occurred
                    among Chinese soldiers at that place morning of May 26th, mutineers in control.
                    Other railway reports state trouble among Chinese soldiers at Muling and
                    Makiaoho stations. Mutineers claim to be supporters Wu Pei-fu. Legation
                    informed.</p>
                <p>In case serious trouble develops at Harbin, which I doubt, what would
                    Department’s instructions be in regard to requesting Japanese military to
                    protect Americans and American property.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hanson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
